Absorption spectra of these products were also recorded. C-Au-1, C-Au-2, C-Au-3 and C-Au-5 exhibited appearance of a significant absorbance in the wavelength range of 500–700nm, which is consistent with the substantial elongation (Fig. 2
                           ). This indicated that some AuNPs were obtained but the AuNPs were not spherical [36,37] (Fig. S4). However, C-Au-4 had an obvious absorption peak at 518nm (Fig. 2, C-Au-4), which strongly indicated the formation of AuNPs. At the same time, the lack of absorption near 600–700nm indicated that the final products are nearly spherical or dot shape [37,38]. Considering the color and the shape of five different productions, we chose 6.0×10–2
                           mg/mL r-CDs and 0.10mM HAuCl4 to prepare AuNPs.

We synthesized AuNPs under different temperatures. It was noticed that no AuNPs was obtained at room temperature even after 24h incubation. However, solution became wine red after incubating mixture of r-CDs and HAuCl4 at 40°C for 24h (Fig. S5). Furthermore, the wine red deepened with the increasing incubating temperature from 40 to 80°C. And the related absorption near 520nm increased with the increasing temperature, too (Fig. 3
                           (a)), which indicated the yield of AuNPs increased. However, as the incubation temperature increased to 100°C, no obvious absorption peak could be observed (Fig. 3(a)), indicating a low yield of AuNPs. After normalized (Fig. 3(b)), it was obvious that the wavelength of the synthesized AuNPs at 60°C underwent a slight red shift compared with the AuNPs obtained at other temperature which could deduce that the size of AuNPs synthesized at 60°C are the largest, which were confirmed in TEM subsequently (Fig. 4
                           ).
